</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,256,2038]" box="[151,1436,1459,1481]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">
9(4) Pronotal posterior lobe glabrous but with uneven, wrinkled or lacunose surface................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1412,1436,1459,1480]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">12</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,256,2038]" box="[151,1436,1488,1510]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">
- Pronotal posterior lobe punctate-setose................................................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1412,1436,1488,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">10</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,256,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">
10 Body rather slim, black-blue to violaceous-blue. Pronotal disc rather densely irregularly transversely striate-rugulose. Temples very short, 2.8–3.2 times shorter than eyes. Elytral apex of female with rounded inner area lacking sutural emargination. Aedeagus rather short, only moderately bent in middle, its apex narrow, slightly bent dorsally. Pronotal posterior lobe covered with large setigerous punctures....................................................... 
